<TITLE> Muslims mark Eid </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Dec 21 (bdnews24.com)  Muslims in the country are celebrating their second biggest religious festival, the Eid-ul Azha, Friday although the fanfare was largely subdued in the cyclone-hit southern regions. Dhaka City Corporation arranged 360 Eid prayer congregations or jamaats in the city's 90 wards. The main congregation was held at the National Eidgah at 8:00am. Senior Pesh imam mufti Mohammad Nuruddin of the Baitul Mukarram National Mosque led the prayers. President Iajuddin Ahmed, speaker Jamiruddin Sircar, chief justice Md Ruhul Amin, foreign affairs adviser Iftekhar Ahmed Chowdhury, Dhaka mayor Sadek Hossain Khoka and other distinguished personalities joined the prayers with ordinary people. Baitul Mukarram National Mosque held five congregations, beginning with the first at 7:00am, followed by the second at 8:00am, the third at 9:00am, the fourth at 10:00am and the final congregation at 10:45am. The last congregation in the city was held at Azimpur Dayera Sharif Dayemia Shahi Jame Mosque at 11:25am. Iajuddin exchanged Eid greetings at the Bangabhaban from 9:30am with people from a broader spectrum of society. The country's largest congregation took place at Sholakia in Kishoreganj, starting at 9:15am Friday. Khatib maulana Abul Khair Mohammed Saifullah of the local Bara Bazaar Jamia Mosque led the congregation. In Chittagong, the main congregation took place at Jamiatul Fallah National Mosque at 8:00am. Another congregation was held at Laldighi Maidan at 8:30am. Sylhet's main congregation was held at the Shahi Eidgah at 8:30am. The second main congregation was held at the Hazrat Shah Jalal Dargah at 9:00am and Hazrat Shah Paran Dargah at 8:30am. Rajshahi's main congregation took place at the Hazrat Shah Makhdum Eidgah at 8:00am. The main congregation in Barisal was held in the Hemayet Uddin playground at 8:00am and Khulna's main jamaat was held at the Circuit House playground at 8:00am. bdnew
